🧠 CORE ROUTE 53 CONCEPTS

> Hosted Zone
A hosted zone is a container that holds DNS records for a domain. There are two types: public hosted zones, which are accessible from the internet, and private hosted zones, which work only inside a VPC.

> DNS Records
DNS records define how traffic is routed. Common records include A records for IPv4 addresses, AAAA records for IPv6, and CNAME or Alias records for mapping domain names to AWS resources.

> Alias Records
Alias records are AWS-specific and are used instead of CNAMEs for AWS services like Load Balancers or CloudFront. They are free and work at the root domain level.

> Health Checks
Health checks monitor the availability of endpoints. Route 53 uses them to decide whether traffic should be routed to an endpoint or not.

> TTL (Time to Live)
TTL defines how long DNS responses are cached by clients. Lower TTL means faster changes but more DNS queries; higher TTL means better performance but slower updates.

🚦 ROUTE 53 ROUTING POLICIES (VERY IMPORTANT FOR INTERVIEWS)

> Simple Routing
Used when there is only one resource. Route 53 returns a single IP address.

> Weighted Routing
Traffic is distributed based on assigned weights. Commonly used for A/B testing or gradual deployments.

> Latency-Based Routing
Traffic is routed to the AWS region with the lowest latency for the user.

> Failover Routing
Used for disaster recovery. Traffic goes to a primary endpoint, and if it fails, Route 53 routes traffic to a secondary endpoint.

> Geolocation Routing
Routes traffic based on the user’s geographic location, such as country or continent.

> Geoproximity Routing
Routes traffic based on distance and allows biasing traffic toward specific locations
